Undoubtedly, the concentration of GSH in wine could affect the taste, fragrance, and expiration date. Due to its antioxidant ability in red wine, a permitted high concentration of GSH could make the wine more delicious, and a higher taste quality of wine [42]. As demonstrated in Fig. 7
                        , the prepared different concentrations of GSH (0, 50, 100, 200, 300, 400, 500, 600, 700 μM) that dropped on the papers were treated as control. While the original wine will affect the authenticity due to its crimson, thus it was transparent after filtering through activated carbon. The blue color of the papers vanished in the case of filtered wine. Referring to the case of added GSH, we can determine that the GSH concentration in wine was ≥400 µM. In the comparison of the traditional methods (HPLC-MS, Chromatographic) for GSH detection in wines, the result indicated that the paper-based colorimetric strategy provided a possible respect for a simple and convenient detection method of GSH in red wine (Table 2
                        ).
